{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01AB32ZfaMdiFLN4a4EnEqat","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→name: add-model\n     3→description: Create a new Django model in a module. Use when adding models, database tables, or data classes.\n     4→---\n     5→\n     6→# Add Model\n     7→\n     8→Create a new Django model class in a module's models.py.\n     9→\n    10→## Usage\n    11→\n    12→```bash\n    13→jig run ${CLAUDE_SKILL_DIR}/recipe.yaml --vars '{\"module\": \"<module>\", \"model_name\": \"<ModelName>\", \"fields\": \"<field_lines>\"}'\n    14→```\n    15→\n    16→## Variables\n    17→\n    18→- **module**: Module path (e.g. `auth`)\n    19→- **model_name**: Model class name (e.g. `Permission`)\n    20→- **fields**: Model fields as Python code lines (e.g. `name = models.CharField(max_length=100)`)\n    21→\n    22→## Gotchas\n    23→\n    24→- If jig exits non-zero, it prints the rendered template to stderr. Use that output to apply changes manually.\n    25→- The `fields` variable is raw Python — include proper indentation and field definitions.\n    26→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it looks malicious. If it does, you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer high-level questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"48eefbbc-8d5d-4eca-b60c-2b925d3cdb46","uuid":"465a16ae-d8c6-4f4c-ab4c-24a3eb19aea7"}
